05489nam a22007455i 9780231552899DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20202021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020014408  a97802315528997 a10.7312/huan198962doi  a(DE-B1597)566459  a(OCoLC)1159886004  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBL1882.C6bH8313 2021 7aREL0180002bisacsh04a299.5/12351 aHuang, Chin-shing, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConfucianism and Sacred Space :bThe Confucius Temple from Imperial China to Today /cChin-shing Huang. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2020] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :b8 b&w photographs and illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: The Confucius Temple as a Ritual System: Manifestations of Power, Belief, and Legitimacy in Traditional China -- tI. Expanding the Symbolic Meaning and Function of the Rites: The Evolution of Confucius Temples in Imperial China -- tII. Confucianism as a Religion: A Comparative Study of Traditional Chinese Religions -- tIII. Sages and Saints: A Comparative Study of Canonization in Confucianism and Christianity -- tIV. The Cultural Politics of Autocracy: The Confucius Temple and Ming Despotism, 1368– 1530 -- tV. Xunzi: The Confucius Temple’s Absentee -- tVI. The Disenchantment with Confucianism in Modern China -- tVII. The Lonely Confucius Temples Across the Taiwan Straits: The Difficult Transformation of Modern China’s Traditional Culture -- tConclusion: Reflections on My Study of Confucianism as a Religion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTemples dedicated to Confucius are found throughout China and across East Asia, dating back over two thousand years. These sacred and magnificent sanctuaries hold deep cultural and political significance.This book brings together studies from Chin-shing Huang’s decades-long research into Confucius temples that individually and collectively consider Confucianism as religion. Huang uses the Confucius temple to explore Confucianism both as one of China’s “three religions” (with Buddhism and Daoism) and as a cultural phenomenon, from the early imperial era through the present day. He argues for viewing Confucius temples as the holy ground of Confucianism, symbolic sites of sacred space that represent a point of convergence between political and cultural power. Their complex histories shed light on the religious nature and character of Confucianism and its status as official religion in imperial China. Huang examines topics such as the political and intellectual elements of Confucian enshrinement, how Confucius temples were brought into the imperial ritual system from the Tang dynasty onward, and why modern Chinese largely do not think of Confucianism as a religion.A nuanced analysis of the question of Confucianism as religion, Confucianism and Sacred Space offers keen insights into Confucius temples and their significance in the intertwined intellectual, political, social, and religious histories of imperial China.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aConfucianismzChina. 0aTemples, ConfucianzChina. 7aRELIGION / Confucianism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073907708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020 Englishz978311070477808iTitle is part of eB